---
import Layout from '../../../layouts/Layout.astro';
const base = (import.meta.env.BASE_URL || '').replace(/\/$/, '');

const sections = [
  {
    id: 'introduction',
    heading: 'Introduction',
    body: `Acid-base regulation is the set of physiological mechanisms by which the body maintains the hydrogen ion concentration ([H⁺]) of extracellular fluid within the narrow range compatible with normal enzymatic function, protein structure, and cellular metabolism. Because hydrogen ion concentration spans many orders of magnitude in biological systems, it is expressed logarithmically as pH—the negative logarithm (base 10) of [H⁺]. The normal arterial pH range of 7.35–7.45 corresponds to an [H⁺] of approximately 35–45 nanomoles per litre, a concentration far lower than that of any other physiologically regulated ion, yet one whose disturbance—even by a fraction of a pH unit—profoundly alters the activity of nearly every enzyme, receptor, and transport protein in the body. Disturbances outside the range of 6.80 to 7.80 are incompatible with life. For nursing professionals, acid-base regulation is not merely a biochemical abstraction; it is the interpretive framework through which the arterial blood gas (ABG)—one of the most information-dense clinical investigations available—is understood. The nurse who can systematically interpret an ABG and correlate its findings with the patient's clinical presentation is positioned to identify life-threatening derangements, anticipate their causes, and contribute intelligently to their management.`,
  },
  {
    id: 'buffer-systems',
    heading: 'Buffer Systems',
    body: `A buffer is a weak acid and its conjugate base (or a weak base and its conjugate acid) in solution that resists changes in pH when strong acids or bases are added. The body employs three principal buffer systems that operate in a coordinated and mathematically interrelated fashion: the bicarbonate-carbonic acid system, the phosphate buffer system, and protein buffers (including haemoglobin).

The Bicarbonate-Carbonic Acid System. The most clinically important buffer system in the ECF, the bicarbonate system is captured in the Henderson-Hasselbalch equation: pH = 6.1 + log ([HCO₃⁻] / [H₂CO₃]). Because carbonic acid (H₂CO₃) is in rapid equilibrium with dissolved carbon dioxide (CO₂) via the enzyme carbonic anhydrase, and because dissolved CO₂ is proportional to the partial pressure of CO₂ in arterial blood (PaCO₂), the equation can be written in clinically useful form as: pH = 6.1 + log ([HCO₃⁻] / [0.0307 × PaCO₂]). This equation reveals the central insight of acid-base physiology: pH is determined not by the absolute values of bicarbonate or PaCO₂ but by their ratio. A normal pH of 7.40 is maintained when the ratio of HCO₃⁻ (approximately 24 mEq/L) to the dissolved CO₂ component (approximately 1.2 mEq/L) equals approximately 20:1. Any process that alters either variable will shift the ratio and, unless compensated, will shift the pH. The bicarbonate-carbonic acid system is uniquely powerful because its two components are regulated by distinct organ systems—the bicarbonate by the kidneys (metabolic component) and the CO₂ by the lungs (respiratory component)—each of which can compensate for disturbances in the other.

The Phosphate Buffer System. The monohydrogen phosphate / dihydrogen phosphate pair (HPO₄²⁻ / H₂PO₄⁻, pKa 6.8) functions primarily as an intracellular buffer and is particularly important in the renal tubular fluid, where it serves as a titratable acid facilitating urinary hydrogen ion excretion and bicarbonate reclamation.

Protein Buffers. Proteins—particularly haemoglobin in erythrocytes and albumin in plasma—contribute substantially to total body buffering capacity by virtue of their histidine residues, whose imidazole side chains have a pKa of approximately 6.0–7.0 and can accept or donate protons across the physiological pH range. Deoxy-haemoglobin is a more effective buffer than oxyhaemoglobin (the Haldane effect), creating a physiologically important coupling between oxygen transport and CO₂/H⁺ handling in the blood: as red blood cells enter the peripheral capillaries, haemoglobin releases oxygen and becomes a better buffer for the CO₂ and H⁺ generated by tissue metabolism.`,
  },
  {
    id: 'respiratory-regulation',
    heading: 'Respiratory Regulation',
    body: `The lungs regulate acid-base balance by controlling the elimination of CO₂—the volatile acid generated by aerobic cellular metabolism—through alveolar ventilation. CO₂ is produced by tissue metabolism at a rate of approximately 200 mL/minute at rest and transported in the blood in three forms: dissolved in plasma (approximately 5%), as bicarbonate formed in red blood cells via carbonic anhydrase (approximately 90%), and as carbamino compounds bound to haemoglobin (approximately 5%). In the pulmonary capillaries, these reactions are reversed and CO₂ is released into the alveoli for exhalation.

Ventilatory control is mediated by central and peripheral chemoreceptors. Central chemoreceptors located in the ventrolateral medulla are exquisitely sensitive to changes in the pH of cerebrospinal fluid (CSF), which reflects arterial CO₂ tension because CO₂ (unlike H⁺ and HCO₃⁻) crosses the blood-brain barrier freely. When PaCO₂ rises and CSF pH falls, central chemoreceptors stimulate the respiratory centre to increase ventilatory rate and depth, thereby increasing CO₂ elimination and correcting the pH. When PaCO₂ falls and CSF pH rises, ventilatory drive is reduced. Peripheral chemoreceptors in the carotid and aortic bodies are primarily sensitive to arterial PaO₂ and provide the hypoxic ventilatory response; they also respond to pH and PaCO₂, contributing to the fine-tuning of the ventilatory response, particularly in severe acidosis.

Respiratory compensation for metabolic acid-base disturbances is rapid—beginning within minutes and reaching maximum effect within 12–24 hours. In metabolic acidosis, hyperventilation (Kussmaul breathing) reduces PaCO₂, partially restoring the HCO₃⁻/CO₂ ratio and pH. The Winter formula (expected PaCO₂ = 1.5 × [HCO₃⁻] + 8 ± 2) provides the expected PaCO₂ for a given degree of metabolic acidosis; a measured PaCO₂ outside this range suggests a concurrent respiratory acid-base disturbance. In metabolic alkalosis, hypoventilation raises PaCO₂, partially compensating for the elevated bicarbonate, though the compensatory response is limited by the competing stimulus of hypoxaemia.`,
  },
  {
    id: 'renal-regulation',
    heading: 'Renal Regulation',
    body: `The kidneys provide the definitive long-term regulation of acid-base balance by controlling the excretion of hydrogen ions and the reclamation or generation of bicarbonate. Unlike the respiratory system, which responds within minutes, renal compensation is slow—beginning within hours and reaching completion over two to five days—but more powerful, capable of completely normalising bicarbonate and pH in the face of primary respiratory disturbances.

Bicarbonate Reclamation. Approximately 4,500 mEq of bicarbonate is filtered by the glomeruli each day. Nearly all (approximately 85%) is reabsorbed in the proximal tubule via a process involving the secretion of H⁺ into the tubular lumen by the Na⁺/H⁺ exchanger (NHE3), which combines with filtered HCO₃⁻ to form H₂CO₃, which is rapidly dehydrated to CO₂ and H₂O by brush-border carbonic anhydrase (carbonic anhydrase IV). The CO₂ diffuses into the proximal tubular cell, where intracellular carbonic anhydrase (CA II) rehydrates it to H₂CO₃, which ionises to H⁺ (recycled for secretion) and HCO₃⁻ (transported across the basolateral membrane into the blood via NBC1). The remaining bicarbonate is reclaimed in the thick ascending limb and the collecting duct.

New Bicarbonate Generation. In the distal nephron (collecting duct type A intercalated cells), H⁺ is secreted into the tubular lumen via a proton-translocating ATPase (H⁺-ATPase) and, to a lesser extent, an H⁺/K⁺-ATPase. This secreted H⁺ is buffered in the tubular fluid by titratable acids—principally phosphate (which is filtered and becomes the vehicle for H⁺ excretion as H₂PO₄⁻) and, most importantly, ammonia. Ammoniagenesis—the production of ammonia (NH₃) from glutamine in the proximal tubular cells and its trapping as ammonium (NH₄⁺) in the collecting duct—represents the dominant mechanism for urinary acid excretion and can increase dramatically in response to chronic acidosis, allowing excretion of hundreds of mEq of H⁺ per day. For each H⁺ excreted by these mechanisms, one new HCO₃⁻ is added to the blood, regenerating bicarbonate consumed in buffering extracellular acid loads.

Aldosterone and acid-base regulation. Aldosterone promotes not only sodium reabsorption but also H⁺ secretion by the type A intercalated cells of the collecting duct. Volume depletion, by activating the RAAS and secondarily increasing aldosterone, therefore produces a metabolic alkalosis—the so-called "contraction alkalosis"—that is maintained by the kidney's prioritisation of volume conservation over pH correction.`,
  },
  {
    id: 'acid-base-disorders',
    heading: 'Primary Acid-Base Disorders',
    body: `Four primary acid-base disorders are defined by the direction of pH change and the primary variable affected: metabolic acidosis (pH < 7.35, HCO₃⁻ decreased), metabolic alkalosis (pH > 7.45, HCO₃⁻ increased), respiratory acidosis (pH < 7.35, PaCO₂ increased), and respiratory alkalosis (pH > 7.45, PaCO₂ decreased). Mixed disorders occur when two or more primary disorders are simultaneously present.

Metabolic Acidosis is characterised by a primary decrease in bicarbonate and is approached via the anion gap (AG = Na⁺ − [Cl⁻ + HCO₃⁻]; normal 8–12 mEq/L). High-AG metabolic acidosis is caused by the accumulation of unmeasured anions and is most commonly attributed to lactic acidosis (tissue hypoperfusion, liver failure, metformin toxicity), diabetic ketoacidosis (DKA), starvation ketosis, uraemic acidosis (chronic kidney disease), and toxic ingestions (salicylates, methanol, ethylene glycol). The mnemonic MUDPILES (Methanol, Uraemia, DKA, Propylene glycol, Isoniazid/Iron, Lactic acidosis, Ethylene glycol, Salicylates) provides a clinical aide-mémoire. Normal-AG (hyperchloraemic) metabolic acidosis results from direct HCO₃⁻ loss or failure of H⁺ excretion without accumulation of unmeasured anions: causes include diarrhoea (gastrointestinal HCO₃⁻ loss), renal tubular acidosis (RTA), early renal failure, and post-hypocapnia. Clinical manifestations include Kussmaul breathing, nausea, vomiting, abdominal pain (especially in DKA), altered consciousness, and cardiovascular depression with severe acidaemia.

Metabolic Alkalosis is defined by a primary increase in bicarbonate, most commonly caused by hydrochloric acid loss (vomiting, nasogastric suction, loop or thiazide diuretics, primary hyperaldosteronism, or Cushing syndrome) or, less commonly, by exogenous alkali administration or severe hypokalaemia (which drives intracellular H⁺ out of cells in exchange for K⁺, and promotes renal H⁺ secretion). Metabolic alkalosis is further categorised as chloride-responsive (urine chloride < 25 mEq/L, reflecting volume depletion with avid chloride reabsorption; corrected by saline administration) or chloride-resistant (urine chloride > 40 mEq/L, reflecting ongoing mineralocorticoid excess; not corrected by saline). Manifestations include hypoventilation, hypokalaemia (as K⁺ shifts intracellularly in alkalosis), hypocalcaemia (as alkalosis increases protein binding of calcium), muscle cramps, and tetany.

Respiratory Acidosis results from alveolar hypoventilation with CO₂ retention (PaCO₂ > 45 mmHg). Acute respiratory acidosis is caused by airway obstruction, central respiratory depression (opioids, benzodiazepines, brainstem injury), acute pulmonary pathology (severe pneumonia, pulmonary oedema, pneumothorax), neuromuscular disease affecting respiratory muscles (myasthenia gravis, Guillain-Barré syndrome), or chest wall abnormalities. Chronic respiratory acidosis develops over days in conditions such as chronic obstructive pulmonary disease (COPD), obesity hypoventilation syndrome, and kyphoscoliosis, during which time the kidneys generate new bicarbonate to partially compensate. The distinction between acute and chronic respiratory acidosis is clinically important: the expected HCO₃⁻ in acute respiratory acidosis increases by approximately 1 mEq/L for every 10 mmHg rise in PaCO₂; in chronic respiratory acidosis, it increases by approximately 3.5 mEq/L per 10 mmHg rise. Manifestations include confusion, somnolence, headache (from cerebral vasodilation), and CO₂ narcosis at very high PaCO₂ levels.

Respiratory Alkalosis results from alveolar hyperventilation with CO₂ loss (PaCO₂ < 35 mmHg). Common causes include anxiety, pain, fever, early sepsis, hepatic encephalopathy, salicylate toxicity (central respiratory stimulation), mechanical hyperventilation, pregnancy (progesterone-driven), and early hypoxaemia. Manifestations include light-headedness, perioral and digital paraesthesiae (from reduced ionised calcium as alkalosis increases albumin binding), carpopedal spasm, and, in severe cases, loss of consciousness or seizures. Renal compensation (bicarbonate wasting) is slow, occurring over 2–5 days.`,
  },
  {
    id: 'abg-interpretation',
    heading: 'Arterial Blood Gas Interpretation',
    body: `The arterial blood gas (ABG) provides a real-time window into the respiratory and metabolic acid-base status of the patient, as well as oxygenation. A systematic interpretive approach prevents errors of premature closure and ensures that mixed disorders are identified.

Step 1: Assess pH. Is the pH acidaemic (< 7.35), alkalaemic (> 7.45), or normal (7.35–7.45)? Note that a "normal" pH does not exclude a significant acid-base disorder if two opposing disturbances are simultaneously present (mixed disorders).

Step 2: Identify the primary disorder. Examine PaCO₂ (normal 35–45 mmHg) and HCO₃⁻ (normal 22–26 mEq/L). If pH is low: acidosis is present. If PaCO₂ is elevated (> 45 mmHg) and is consistent with the pH direction, the primary disorder is respiratory acidosis. If HCO₃⁻ is low (< 22 mEq/L) and is consistent with the pH direction, the primary disorder is metabolic acidosis. If pH is high: alkalosis is present. Analogously, elevated HCO₃⁻ indicates primary metabolic alkalosis; decreased PaCO₂ indicates primary respiratory alkalosis.

Step 3: Assess compensation. For each primary disorder, determine whether the compensatory response is appropriate using established formulae. Metabolic acidosis: expected PaCO₂ = (1.5 × HCO₃⁻) + 8 ± 2 (Winter's formula). Metabolic alkalosis: expected PaCO₂ = (0.7 × HCO₃⁻) + 21 ± 2. Acute respiratory acidosis: expected HCO₃⁻ increase = 0.1 × ΔPCO₂. Chronic respiratory acidosis: expected HCO₃⁻ increase = 0.35 × ΔPCO₂. Respiratory alkalosis (acute): expected HCO₃⁻ decrease = 0.2 × ΔPCO₂. Respiratory alkalosis (chronic): expected HCO₃⁻ decrease = 0.5 × ΔPCO₂. A compensatory response outside the expected range indicates a concurrent second primary acid-base disorder.

Step 4: Calculate the anion gap (if metabolic acidosis is present). AG = Na⁺ − (Cl⁻ + HCO₃⁻). If AG > 12 mEq/L, calculate the delta-delta ratio (ΔAG / ΔHCO₃⁻) to screen for a concurrent metabolic alkalosis or normal-AG acidosis. A delta-delta ratio > 2 suggests an underlying metabolic alkalosis; < 1 suggests a concurrent normal-AG acidosis.

Step 5: Assess oxygenation. PaO₂ (normal 80–100 mmHg on room air) and oxygen saturation (SaO₂, normal ≥ 95%) assess oxygenation. The alveolar-arterial (A-a) gradient—calculated as the difference between the alveolar PO₂ (PAO₂) and the measured PaO₂—distinguishes hypoxaemia caused by hypoventilation (normal A-a gradient) from that caused by V/Q mismatch, diffusion limitation, or shunt (elevated A-a gradient). PAO₂ = (FiO₂ × [Patm − PH₂O]) − (PaCO₂ / RQ), where FiO₂ is the fractional inspired oxygen concentration, Patm is atmospheric pressure (760 mmHg at sea level), PH₂O is the water vapour pressure at 37°C (47 mmHg), and RQ (respiratory quotient) is assumed to be 0.8. The normal A-a gradient is approximately 5–15 mmHg in young adults breathing room air and increases with age.`,
  },
  {
    id: 'nursing-applications',
    heading: 'Applications in Nursing Practice',
    body: `The clinical implications of acid-base physiology for nursing practice span assessment, monitoring, pharmacological management support, airway management, and patient education.

ABG Sampling and Handling. Nurses in many clinical settings are responsible for obtaining arterial blood gas specimens via radial, femoral, or brachial arterial puncture, or from indwelling arterial lines. Correct technique requires the Allen's test (for radial puncture) to confirm adequate ulnar collateral circulation, use of a heparinised syringe, prompt transport on ice (to prevent ongoing cellular metabolism from altering pH and gas values), and application of adequate pressure to the puncture site for 5–10 minutes (longer in patients receiving anticoagulants). Specimens must be processed within 30 minutes of collection.

Systematic ABG Interpretation. Nurses are expected to interpret ABG results systematically and correlate findings with the clinical presentation. Identifying a severe respiratory acidosis with rising PaCO₂ in a patient with worsening consciousness is a clinical emergency requiring escalation; recognising an ABG consistent with metabolic alkalosis in a patient receiving nasogastric suction provides the interpretive context for a serum potassium of 3.1 mEq/L and the rationale for chloride-containing fluid replacement.

Ventilatory Support Management. For patients receiving mechanical ventilation, nurses must understand the relationship between ventilator settings and acid-base status. An increase in respiratory rate or tidal volume (minute ventilation) increases CO₂ elimination and reduces PaCO₂, treating respiratory acidosis or inducing respiratory alkalosis. Nurses must be prepared to identify and report ventilator alarms, assess endotracheal tube position, and recognise the consequences of inadvertent hyperventilation (respiratory alkalosis, cerebral vasoconstriction with potential ischaemia in the setting of raised intracranial pressure) or hypoventilation (CO₂ retention, worsening acidosis).

Management of Specific Acid-Base Disorders. In diabetic ketoacidosis, nursing management centres on careful fluid and insulin administration, hourly monitoring of urine output and serum glucose, and serial ABG or venous blood gas (VBG) monitoring to track the resolution of acidosis and prevent hypokalaemia as potassium shifts back intracellularly with insulin therapy. In patients with COPD and chronic hypercapnia, nurses must be cautious with supplemental oxygen therapy: high-flow oxygen can suppress the hypoxic drive, worsen hypoventilation, and precipitate acute-on-chronic respiratory acidosis. Targeted oxygen therapy maintaining SpO₂ at 88–92% in documented CO₂ retainers is the evidence-based standard.

Sodium Bicarbonate Administration. Intravenous sodium bicarbonate is used selectively in severe metabolic acidosis (pH < 7.10–7.15, particularly uraemic acidosis, renal tubular acidosis, or bicarbonate-wasting states), severe hyperkalaemia, and tricyclic antidepressant toxicity. Nurses must administer bicarbonate with caution, recognising that rapid correction can paradoxically worsen intracellular acidosis (as CO₂ generated from the administered bicarbonate crosses cell membranes more readily than bicarbonate itself), induce metabolic alkalosis if excess is given, and precipitate hypokalaemia and hypocalcaemia.

Patient Education. Patients with conditions predisposing to recurrent acid-base disturbances—including diabetes mellitus, chronic kidney disease, COPD, and cardiac failure—benefit from education on recognition of warning symptoms (unusual breathlessness, confusion, polyuria, nausea), the importance of medication adherence, and the indications for seeking urgent medical assessment. For patients managing diabetes, recognition of the early symptoms of DKA and the use of ketone monitoring (urine or blood) are critical self-management skills that nurses are well positioned to teach.`,
  },
  {
    id: 'conclusion',
    heading: 'Conclusion',
    body: `Acid-base regulation is a physiological domain of extraordinary precision and clinical significance. The maintenance of arterial pH within the narrow range of 7.35–7.45 requires the seamless integration of chemical buffer systems, pulmonary ventilatory control, and renal tubular acid excretion, each operating across different time scales and with distinct regulatory priorities. Disruptions to this system—whether metabolic or respiratory in origin, acute or chronic, simple or mixed—produce clinical syndromes whose recognition depends on the systematic interpretation of the arterial blood gas in the context of the patient's history, physical examination, and concurrent biochemical data. For the nursing student, the mastery of acid-base physiology and ABG interpretation represents a significant intellectual investment that yields immediate and lifelong clinical dividends. The ability to move fluidly between the abstract language of pH, PaCO₂, and bicarbonate and the concrete clinical reality of a breathless, confused patient at the bedside is the hallmark of the clinically competent nurse—one who understands not merely what is happening, but why, and what to do about it.`,
  },
];

const renderPara = (para) => {
  const dotIdx = para.indexOf('. ');
  if (dotIdx > 0 && dotIdx < para.length - 2) {
    const phrase = para.slice(0, dotIdx + 1);
    if (phrase.split(/\s+/).length <= 6) {
      return `<strong>${phrase}</strong> ${para.slice(dotIdx + 2)}`;
    }
  }
  return para;
};
